That flash of invisible text, or the jolt when your headline swaps fonts — both are choices the browser is making for you, and you can take the wheel.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

Open a fresh page on a slow connection and watch the text closely. One of two things happens. Either the text is invisible for a beat and then appears — or it appears immediately in a fallback font and then snaps to your custom font a moment later. These have names: FOIT (Flash of Invisible Text) and FOUT (Flash of Unstyled Text). Neither is a bug. They’re the two strategies a browser can use while a web font downloads, and font-display is how you tell it which one you want.
Let’s get under the hood.
Why there’s a flash at all
A web font is a file — often 20–100KB even after WOFF2 compression. It has to be downloaded before the browser can render text with it. But text is usually ready to paint long before the font arrives. So the browser faces a dilemma during that gap:
Show nothing, or show something?

• Show nothing → FOIT. No layout jump, but the user stares at blank space. If the font is slow or fails, they might see nothing readable for seconds.

• Show a fallback → FOUT. Content is readable instantly, but when the real font loads, the text re-renders and can shift.
This window — between text being ready and the font being available — is governed by a “block period” and a “swap period.” font-display lets you set the policy.
The font-display values, decoded
This descriptor goes inside your @font-face rule and controls the whole dance:
@font-face {
font-family: 'Inter';
src: url('/fonts/inter.woff2') format('woff2');
font-weight: 100 900;
font-display: swap; /* the lever */
}Here’s what each value actually does:

• auto — Leaves it to the browser. In practice most browsers default to FOIT-like behavior with a ~3s block. You usually don't want this by accident.

• block — Short block period (text invisible), then swaps. Classic FOIT. The text is hidden up to ~3s waiting for the font. Use only when text in the wrong font is genuinely unacceptable (rare).

• swap — Effectively no block period. Text shows in the fallback immediately, then swaps when the font loads. Classic FOUT. Best for readability — content is never invisible. The cost: a potential layout shift on swap.

• fallback — A tiny block (~100ms), a short swap window (~3s). If the font is late, the fallback sticks for the rest of the page view. A compromise: minimal invisibility, minimal shift, accepts that slow fonts just don't show.

• optional — Tiny block, no swap period. The browser uses the font only if it's already available (or can grab it instantly); otherwise it sticks with the fallback and quietly downloads the font for next time. Best for zero layout shift. The custom font may simply not appear on first visit.
The honest default for body text is swap: never hide content from your user. The default for "I cannot tolerate any layout shift" is optional.
The hidden cost of FOUT: layout shift
swap sounds like the obvious winner — readable instantly — but it has a tax. The fallback font and your web font have different metrics: different character widths, line heights, x-heights. When the swap happens, a paragraph that was 5 lines tall might become 4, and everything below it jumps up. That jump is Cumulative Layout Shift (CLS), a Core Web Vital, and font swaps are one of its most common causes.
The fix is to make the fallback and the web font occupy nearly the same space, so the swap is invisible to the eye:
@font-face {
font-family: 'Inter';
src: url('/fonts/inter.woff2') format('woff2');
font-display: swap;
}/* A metric-matched fallback so the swap doesn't move anything */
@font-face {
font-family: 'Inter-fallback';
src: local('Arial');
size-adjust: 107%; /* tune so glyph widths match */
ascent-override: 90%;
descent-override: 22%;
line-gap-override: 0%;
}body {
font-family: 'Inter', 'Inter-fallback', sans-serif;
}size-adjust and the *-override descriptors let you reshape a system font to match your web font's box. Tuned well, you get FOUT's instant readability without FOUT's jump. This is the technique that separates "good enough" from "actually polished."
Preload the fonts that matter
font-display decides what to do during the wait. Preloading shrinks the wait itself. By default, the browser only discovers a font after it parses the CSS and finds an element that needs it — late in the pipeline. Preloading kicks the download off immediately:
<link rel="preload" href="/fonts/inter.woff2" as="font" type="font/woff2" crossorigin>Two non-negotiables here:

• crossorigin is required, even for same-origin fonts. Fonts are always fetched in CORS mode; omit it and the browser downloads the font twice — once for the preload, once for real. A classic silent waste.

• Preload sparingly. Only the fonts used above the fold (your headline and primary body weight). Preloading every weight and italic competes with your LCP image for bandwidth and can make things slower, not faster.
Putting it together: a sane default setup
For most sites, this combination gives readable-instantly text with no visible jump:

• font-display: swap on your primary fonts.

• A metric-matched fallback with size-adjust so the swap is invisible.

• preload for only the above-the-fold weights, with crossorigin.

• WOFF2 only — it’s the smallest format and universally supported now.
<link rel="preload" href="/fonts/inter-var.woff2" as="font" type="font/woff2" crossorigin>@font-face {
font-family: 'Inter';
src: url('/fonts/inter-var.woff2') format('woff2-variations');
font-weight: 100 900; /* one variable font, every weight */
font-display: swap;
}A variable font is a bonus: one file covers every weight, so you preload once instead of juggling regular/bold/italic downloads.
What happens if you ignore fonts
You ship font-display: auto, the browser blocks text for up to three seconds on a slow connection, and a user on mobile sees a blank article. Or you fix that with naive swap and now your headline lurches half a line on every page load, tanking your CLS score. Fonts are quietly one of the biggest sources of both invisible text and layout shift — and almost nobody profiles them until a Core Web Vitals report goes red.
Where this connects
The layout-shift side of font loading is part of a bigger metric. If you want to understand how swaps, late images, and injected content all roll up into one score — and how to drive it down — I covered it in depth in the Cumulative Layout Shift breakdown. Fonts are one of the first things I check when a CLS number looks wrong.

